History of the creation of the Facebook network
David Fincher&#39;s new film is, first and foremost, a story about paradox.
The film tells the story of the invention of Facebook, one of the pioneering tools in the Internet sphere, which united the whole world, divided five friends and made its creator - 26-year-old former Harvard student Mark Zuckerberg - the youngest billionaire of the last decades.
Jesse Eisenberg is equally brilliant in the title role as our conflicted genius, an emotionally isolated social outcast with an unpredictable set of motivations and loyalties.
Zuckerberg launches the site for a variety of reasons: partly out of anger at the world around him, partly for sport, and partly because IT&#39;S just &quot;cool.&quot;
The idea itself and its implementation may seem elemental and spontaneous, but the actual course of events hints at a clear calculation and a well-thought-out business plan.
The Social Network&#39;s strengths are evident from the very first frame, particularly in the pre-credits scene where Zuckerberg talks to his soon-to-be ex-girlfriend Erica (Mara) at a bar: screenwriter Aaron Sorkin&#39;s crisp, hard-hitting dialogue picks up steam here and doesn&#39;t let up until the very end.
The same goes for Fincher&#39;s direction: comparatively restrained (with the exception of the Winklevoss twins, the actors are dissimilar to each other.
The face of one of them was superimposed onto the other using computer graphics.
Natalie Portman studied at Harvard at the same time as Zuckerberg.
Rooney Mara has been cast as the lead in Fincher&#39;s next film, The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo.
DIRECTOR David Fincher
STARRING: Jesse Eisenberg, Andrew Garfield, Rooney Mara, Justin Timberlake, Armie Hammer, Joshua Pence
PLOT: Gloomy and withdrawn Harvard student Mark Zuckerberg, having received a cold shoulder on the personal front, takes on the ambitious task of creating a fundamentally new social network.
As Facebook grows in popularity, relationships with a few companion friends begin to deteriorate and eventually lead to lawsuits.
The color palette plays its part: warm, sunny in places, cosy even in the dark, it maneuvers between two tangled chains of events and two separate legal battles.
Outside of the constant stream of discussions, not much happens in the film: not a single death, not a single murder, and all of Zuckerberg&#39;s legal troubles hardly amount to an additional paragraph for his meager Wikipedia page.
What attracted 49-year-old Sorkin and 48-year-old Fincher to this story that is not very generous with details?
After watching it, there is a strong feeling that “The Social Network” is a portrait of our time, and the understatement in this case is an important artistic device.
Just twenty years ago, Wall Street was doing much the same thing, only on a larger scale - with cosmic egos and big deals.
Now that daily solvency has become even higher, policy is no longer implemented at board meetings, but in sandboxes.
Zuckerberg wants to be special, dreams of becoming the center of attention.
Severin (Garfield) is upset that his best friend has a new best friend (Timberlake) and now he has no one to play with.
The Winklevosses (Hammer and Pence), meanwhile, are stamping their feet: who said that the rich, beautiful and athletic can’t also be smart?
(This line particularly amuses Fincher.)
If you wanted, The Social Network could easily have been a black comedy.
Zuckerberg is obsessed with the idea of popularity and leadership, but what is more in his business - positive or negative?
And what social consequences will his invention entail?
Is he a swindler?
Or a cunning manipulator?
Fincher and Sorkin will never close a book if there is even the slightest hint of something like this in it.
But here it won&#39;t even be necessary: in their version of history it doesn&#39;t matter at all.
&quot;How does it feel to be beautiful?&quot; asks Tre VeaNez&#39;s &quot;WaBu Woz&#39;te A Vsp Map,&quot; which pre-credits the song.
The hero doesn&#39;t know.
The film suggests the answer.
Zuckerberg is part of a lost online generation that has little sense of beauty and even less sense of emotion.
