At the beginning of the 17th century, when Ivan Susanin lived, surnames among people of humble origin had not yet really begun to appear.
They got by with the title &quot;such and such, such and such&#39;s son.&quot;
That is, patronymics were in use - nicknames after the father.
But sometimes, for example in the case of the father&#39;s repeated marriages, a matronym was used - a nickname based on the mother&#39;s name.
Susanin is just such a case: “Ivan, son of Susanna.”
Serfs of small landowners actually managed without surnames for a long time - why have one when you have 20 souls and everything is constantly in sight.
But the owners of estates with thousands of people were forced to give their peasants surnames.
Thus, the serfs of Prince Andrei Cherkassky already had surnames without exception at the beginning of the 18th century.
In the 19th century, even small landowners did not keep the peasant on the land, but released him on a quitrent - let him earn money with a craft and pay the owner.
Such a peasant was entitled to a passport, where his surname had to be entered.
By the time serfdom was abolished in Central Russia, 55% of serfs were released on quitrent.
This means they already had surnames.
