Experts were able to prevent the flooding by closing the dam the day before.
On Friday, the threat of flooding in St. Petersburg increased sharply due to bad weather in the city.
The sea surge flood was prevented by the timely closure of the dam.
The potential flood could have been the 32nd, reports the St. Petersburg publication Neva.Today.
The water level reached 184 centimeters, but thanks to the closure of the gates in the Gulf of Finland, the water remained at 168 centimeters, which is only seven centimeters higher than the lower threshold of the dangerous flood level (from 161 to 210 centimeters).
The weather conditions were complicated by gusty winds, the speed of which at times reached 20-25 meters per second.
Now the dam has been opened again, the water level has dropped, and ships can once again navigate the Gulf of Finland.
It should be noted that the water level situation is monitored by ten meteorological stations on the eastern side of the Gulf of Finland.
This helps prevent flooding that could follow stronger winds.
